VI was born and raised in North Korea.
p4
aVAlthough my family constantly struggled against poverty,
p5
aVI was always loved and cared for first,
p6
aVbecause I was the only son
p7
aVand the youngest of two in the family.
p8
aa(lp9
VBut then the great famine began in 1994.
p10
aVI was four years old.
p11
aVMy sister and I would go searching for firewood
p12
aVstarting at 5 in the morning
p13
aVand come back after midnight.
p14
aVI would wander the streets searching for food,
p15
aVand I remember seeing a small child
p16
aVtied to a mother's back eating chips,
p17
aVand wanting to steal them from him.
p18
aa(lp19
VHunger is humiliation. Hunger is hopelessness.
p20
aVFor a hungry child, politics and freedom
p21
aVare not even thought of.
p22
aVOn my ninth birthday, my parents
p23
aVcouldn't give me any food to eat.
p24
aVBut even as a child, I could feel the heaviness
p25
aVin their hearts.
p26
aa(lp27
VOver a million North Koreans died of starvation in that time,
p28
aVand in 2003, when I was 13 years old,
p29
aVmy father became one of them.
p30
aVI saw my father wither away and die.
p31
aVIn the same year, my mother disappeared one day,
p32
aVand then my sister told me
p33
aVthat she was going to China to earn money,
p34
aVbut that she would return with money and food soon.
p35
aVSince we had never been separated,
p36
aVand I thought we would be together forever,
p37
aVI didn't even give her a hug when she left.
p38
aVIt was the biggest mistake I have ever made in my life.
p39
aVBut again, I didn't know
p40
aVit was going to be a long goodbye.
p41
aVI have not seen my mom or my sister since then.
p42
aa(lp43
VSuddenly, I became an orphan and homeless.
p44
aVMy daily life became very hard,
p45
aVbut very simple.
p46
aVMy goal was to find a dusty piece of bread in the trash.
p47
aVBut that is no way to survive.
p48
aVI started to realize, begging would not be the solution.
p49
aVSo I started to steal from food carts in illegal markets.
p50
aVSometimes, I found small jobs
p51
aVin exchange for food.
p52
aVOnce, I even spent two months in the winter
p53
aVworking in a coal mine,
p54
aV33 meters underground without any protection
p55
aVfor up to 16 hours a day.
p56
aVI was not uncommon.
p57
aVMany other orphans survived this way, or worse.
p58
aa(lp59
VWhen I could not fall asleep from bitter cold
p60
aVor hunger pains,
p61
aVI hoped that, the next morning,
p62
aVmy sister would come back to wake me up
p63
aVwith my favorite food.
p64
aVThat hope kept me alive.
p65
aVI don't mean big, grand hope.
p66
aVI mean the kind of hope that made me believe
p67
aVthat the next trash can had bread,
p68
aVeven though it usually didn't.
p69
aVBut if I didn't believe it, I wouldn't even try,
p70
aVand then I would die.
p71
aVHope kept me alive.
p72
aVEvery day, I told myself,
p73
aVno matter how hard things got,
p74
aVstill I must live.
p75
aa(lp76
VAfter three years of waiting for my sister's return,
p77
aVI decided to go to China to look for her myself.
p78
aVI realized
p79
aVI couldn't survive much longer this way.
p80
aVI knew the journey would be risky,
p81
aVbut I would be risking my life either way.
p82
aVI could die of starvation like my father in North Korea,
p83
aVor at least I could try for a better life
p84
aVby escaping to China.
p85
aa(lp86
VI had learned that many people tried to cross
p87
aVthe border to China in the nighttime to avoid being seen.
p88
aVNorth Korean border guards often shoot and kill people
p89
aVtrying to cross the border without permission.
p90
aVChinese soldiers will catch
p91
aVand send back North Koreans,
p92
aVwhere they face severe punishment.
p93
aVI decided to cross during the day,
p94
aVfirst because I was still a kid and scared of the dark,
p95
aVsecond because I knew I was already taking a risk,
p96
aVand since not many people tried to cross during the day,
p97
aVI thought I might be able to cross
p98
aVwithout being seen by anyone.
p99
aa(lp100
VI made it to China on February 15, 2006.
p101
aVI was 16 years old.
p102
aVI thought things in China would be easier,
p103
aVsince there was more food.
p104
aVI thought more people would help me.
p105
aVBut it was harder than living in North Korea,
p106
aVbecause I was not free.
p107
aVI was always worried about being caught
p108
aVand sent back.
p109
aa(lp110
VBy a miracle, some months later,
p111
aVI met someone who was running
p112
aVan underground shelter for North Koreans,
p113
aVand was allowed to live there
p114
aVand eat regular meals for the first time in many years.
p115
aVLater that year, an activist helped me escape China
p116
aVand go to the United States as a refugee.
p117
aa(lp118
VI went to America without knowing a word of English,
p119
aVyet my social worker told me that I had to go to high school.
p120
aVEven in North Korea, I was an F student.
p121
aV(Laughter)
p122
aVAnd I barely finished elementary school.
p123
aVAnd I remember I fought in school more than once a day.
p124
aVTextbooks and the library were not my playground.
p125
aVMy father tried very hard to motivate me into studying,
p126
aVbut it didn't work.
p127
aVAt one point, my father gave up on me.
p128
aVHe said, "You're not my son anymore."
p129
aVI was only 11 or 12, but it hurt me deeply.
p130
aVBut nevertheless, my level of motivation
p131
aVstill didn't change before he died.
p132
aVSo in America, it was kind of ridiculous
p133
aVthat they said I should go to high school.
p134
aVI didn't even go to middle school.
p135
aVI decided to go, just because they told me to,
p136
aVwithout trying much.
p137
aa(lp138
VBut one day, I came home and my foster mother
p139
aVhad made chicken wings for dinner.
p140
aVAnd during dinner, I wanted to have one more wing,
p141
aVbut I realized there were not enough for everyone,
p142
aVso I decided against it.
p143
aVWhen I looked down at my plate,
p144
aVI saw the last chicken wing, that my foster father had given me his.
p145
aVI was so happy.
p146
aVI looked at him sitting next to me.
p147
aVHe just looked back at me very warmly,
p148
aVbut said no words.
p149
aVSuddenly I remembered my biological father.
p150
aVMy foster father's small act of love
p151
aVreminded me of my father,
p152
aVwho would love to share his food with me
p153
aVwhen he was hungry, even if he was starving.
p154
aVI felt so suffocated that I had so much food in America,
p155
aVyet my father died of starvation.
p156
aVMy only wish that night was to cook a meal for him,
p157
aVand that night I also thought of what else I could do
p158
aVto honor him.
p159
aVAnd my answer was to promise to myself
p160
aVthat I would study hard and get the best education
p161
aVin America to honor his sacrifice.
p162
aa(lp163
VI took school seriously,
p164
aVand for the first time ever in my life,
p165
aVI received an academic award for excellence,
p166
aVand made dean's list from the first semester in high school.
p167
